File Name: 01_basic_queries.sql


Description:
This SQL script contains a structured set of foundational queries used to explore
and analyze football match data from the Premier League dataset. The purpose of
this file is to apply basic SQL techniques on a real-world dataset and extract
meaningful insights in a clear and simple way.


Objective:
The script was created as the first step of the project, focusing on the use of
standard SQL functions and clean query structure. It demonstrates how raw football
data can be transformed into useful information through straightforward analysis.


Topics Covered:
The queries in this file examine questions such as:

- How many matches, teams, and seasons are included in the dataset
- What is the time range of the dataset (first and last match)
- How many goals are scored overall and on average per match
- How goals are distributed across matches (0, low, and high scoring games)
- How match outcomes are distributed (home wins, away wins, draws)
- What percentage of matches end in each result category
- What is the average number of cards per match (total, yellow, red)
- What is the maximum number of cards recorded in a single match


SQL Concepts Used:
This file mainly uses simple and essential SQL concepts, including:

- SELECT
- COUNT, SUM, AVG
- DISTINCT
- UNION / UNION ALL
- GROUP BY
- ORDER BY
- LIMIT
- CASE WHEN
- Basic arithmetic operations on columns


Approach:
The focus of this script is clarity and structure. The analysis is divided into
separate sections, each addressing a specific aspect of the dataset:

- Section 1: Dataset Overview
- Section 2: Goals & Scoring
- Section 3: Match Outcomes
- Section 4: Discipline (Cards)

Each section contains simple, readable queries that answer practical analytical
questions without using advanced SQL techniques.


Results:
The output of these queries provides a clear overview of the dataset, including
scoring behavior, match outcome patterns, and disciplinary trends. These results
serve as a foundation for further analysis and can be used for visualization or
reporting in later stages of the project.


Notes:
This file represents the introductory stage of the project. The emphasis is on
building a solid understanding of SQL fundamentals while working with real data.
It is designed to be easily readable and extendable, forming the base for more
advanced analysis in future scripts.